[("In September 2015, Google engineering manager Rachel Potvin revealed details about Google's software code at an engineering conference.", 'NNP'), ('She revealed that the entire Google codebase, which spans every single service it develops, consists of over 2 billion lines of code.', 'NNP'), ('All that code is stored in a code repository available to all 25,000 Google engineers, and the code is regularly copied and updated on 10 Google data centers.', 'NNP'), ('To keep control, Potvin said Google has built its own "version control system", called "Piper", and that "when you start a new project, you have a wealth of libraries already available to you.', 'NNP'), ('Almost everything has already been done."', 'NNP'), ('Engineers can make a single code change and deploy it on all services at the same time.', 'NNP'), ("The only major exceptions are that the PageRank search results algorithm is stored separately with only specific employee access, and the code for the Android operating system and the Google Chrome browser are also stored separately, as they don't run on the Internet.", 'NNP'), ('The "Piper" system spans 85 TB of data.', 'NNP'), ('Google engineers make 25,000 changes to the code each day and on a weekly basis change approximately 15 million lines of code across 250,000 files.', 'NNP'), ('With that much code, automated bots have to help.', 'NNP'), ('Potvin reported, "You need to make a concerted effort to maintain code health.', 'NNP'), ("And this is not just humans maintaining code health, but robots too. Bots aren't writing code, but generating a lot of the data and configuration files needed to run the company's software.", 'NNP'), ('"Not only is the size of the repository increasing," Potvin explained, "but the rate of change is also increasing.', 'NNP'), ('This is an exponential curve.', 'NNP'), ('"[91][92]', 'NN')]Stentense token :

[('In 2010, Google Energy made its first investment in a renewable energy project, putting $38.8\xa0million into two wind farms in North Dakota.', 'NNP'), ('The company announced the two locations will generate 169.5\xa0megawatts of power, enough to supply 55,000 homes.', 'NNP'), ('The farms, which were developed by NextEra Energy Resources, will reduce fossil fuel use in the region and return profits.', 'NNP'), ('NextEra Energy Resources sold Google a twenty-percent stake in the project to get funding for its development.', 'NNP'), ('[119] In February 2010, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission FERC granted Google an authorization to buy and sell energy at market rates.', 'NNP'), ('[120] The order specifically states that Google Energya subsidiary of Googleholds the rights "for the sale of energy, capacity, and ancillary services at market-based rates", but acknowledges that neither Google Energy nor its affiliates "own or control any generation or transmission" facilities.', 'JJ'), ('[121] The corporation exercised this authorization in September 2013 when it announced it would purchase all the electricity produced by the not-yet-built 240-megawatt Happy Hereford wind farm.', 'JJ'), ('[122]', 'NN')]Stentense token :

[('On August 15, 2011, Google made its largest-ever acquisition to date when it announced that it would acquire Motorola Mobility for $12.5\xa0billion[128][129] subject to approval from regulators in the United States and Europe.', 'JJ'), ("In a post on Google's blog, Google Chief Executive and co-founder Larry Page revealed that the acquisition was a strategic move to strengthen Google's patent portfolio.", 'NNP'), ("The company's Android operating system has come under fire in an industry-wide patent battle, as Apple and Microsoft have sued Android device makers such as HTC, Samsung, and Motorola.", 'NNP'), ('[130] The merger was completed on May 22, 2012, after the approval of China.', 'NNP'), ('[131]', 'NN')]Stentense token : 
This purchase was made in part to help Google gain Motorola's considerable patent portfolio on mobile phones and wireless technologies, to help protect Google in its ongoing patent disputes with other companies,[132] mainly Apple and Microsoft,[130] and to allow it to continue to freely offer Android.

Google offers Gmail, and the newer variant Inbox,[211] for email,[212] Google Calendar for time-management and scheduling,[213] Google Maps for mapping, navigation and satellite imagery,[214] Google Drive for cloud storage of files,[215] Google Docs, Sheets and Slides for productivity,[215] Google Photos for photo storage and sharing,[216] Google Keep for note-taking,[217] Google Translate for language translation,[218] YouTube for video viewing and sharing,[219] Google My Business for managing public business information,[220] and Google+ (which will be closing down on April 2, 2019),[221][222] Allo, and Duo for social interaction.

Google's headquarters in Mountain View, California is referred to as "the Googleplex", a play on words on the number googolplex and the headquarters itself being a complex of buildings.

Recreational amenities are scattered throughout the campus and include a workout room with weights and rowing machines, locker rooms, washers and dryers, a massage room, assorted video games, table football, a baby grand piano, a billiard table, and ping pong.

[357] After two years of silence, during which many wondered what had happened to the program,[358] Google revealed the winners of the project, giving a total of ten million dollars to various ideas ranging from non-profit organizations that promote education to a website that intends to make all legal documents public and online.

[372] However, the project was canceled in 2014, after engineers Ross Koningstein and David Fork understood, after years of study, that "best-case scenario, which was based on our most optimistic forecasts for renewable energy, would still result in severe climate change", writing that they "came to the conclusion that even if Google and others had led the way toward a wholesale adoption of renewable energy, that switch would not have resulted in significant reductions in carbon dioxide emissions".

[('In 2007, Google launched a project centered on developing renewable energy, titled the "Renewable Energy Cheaper than Coal (RE<C)" project.', 'NNP'), ('[372] However, the project was canceled in 2014, after engineers Ross Koningstein and David Fork understood, after years of study, that "best-case scenario, which was based on our most optimistic forecasts for renewable energy, would still result in severe climate change", writing that they "came to the conclusion that even if Google and others had led the way toward a wholesale adoption of renewable energy, that switch would not have resulted in significant reductions in carbon dioxide emissions".', 'CD'), ('[373]', 'NN')]Stentense token :
